<P><PB N="388" REF="424">March 20th, 1656, by an order of common-council, Mr. Richard Prideaux was appointed morning lecturer, and Mr. William Durant afternoon lecturer of this church <NOTE N="s" PLACE="foot"><P>Common-council books.</P>
<P>It appears that this Prideaux conformed; for, Augu&s;t 27th, 1662, we find him &s;ettled here, to preach both forenoon and afternoon.&mdash;He was of the per&s;ua&s;ion then called "The Congregational Judgment."</P></NOTE>.</P>
<P>Augu&s;t 9th, 1663, Mr. Thomas Davi&s;on was appointed lecturer of All-Saints, with a &s;alary of 150l. per annum <NOTE N="t" PLACE="foot">Common-council books.&mdash;See Wood's Fa&s;ti Oxon. Thomas Davi&s;on, A. M. of St. John's, Cambridge, is &s;uppo&s;ed to have been the &s;ame per&s;on who publi&s;hed the Fall of Angels laid open, &amp;c. a &s;ermon preached before the mayor, &amp;c. of Newca&s;tle upon Tyne. London, 1685, 4^t^o.&mdash;Fa&s;ti Oxon. p. 153.</NOTE>.</P>
<P>March 23d, 1664, Mr. William Cock <NOTE N="u" PLACE="foot">Common-council books.</NOTE> was appointed on the re&s;ig|nation of T. Davi&s;on.</P>
<P>January 26th, 1666, Mr. William Bickerton was appointed, with a &s;alary of 100l. on the re&s;ignation of W. Cock <NOTE N="v" PLACE="foot">Co&s;ins' Reg. p. 85. He had been pa&s;tor of Wol&s;ingham during the u&s;urpation. Kennett's Reg. 922.</NOTE>.</P>
<P>May 8th, 1671, Leonard Shaftoe, A. M. was appointed, on the death of W. Bickerton, both forenoon and afternoon lecturer, with a &s;alary of 70l. per annum <NOTE N="w" PLACE="foot">Ibid. p. 89.</NOTE>.</P>
<P><PB N="389" REF="425">Augu&s;t 30th, 1676, William Mayer, A. M. was removed from St. Nicholas' lecture&s;hip to All-Saints, where he was to preach both fore|noon and afternoon; &s;alary 90l. <NOTE N="x" PLACE="foot">Common-council books.</NOTE></P>
<P>November, 1686, on the death of W. Mayer, Mr. Nathanael Elli&s;on was appointed, with a &s;alary of 130l. to preach both forenoons and af|ternoons, and in his turn on Thur&s;day's lecture.&mdash;To allow 20l. per annum out of his &s;alary for an a&s;&s;i&s;tant <NOTE N="y" PLACE="foot">By John March, vicar of Newca&s;tle.&mdash;Extract from the original certificate in Hunter's MSS. vol. ii. No. 157&mdash;he is &s;tyled "&s;on of the late Robert Elli&s;on, merchant."</NOTE>.</P>
<P>Dec. 2d, 1687, Mr. Thomas Knaggs <NOTE N="z" PLACE="foot"><P>Common-council books.&mdash;Thomas Knaggs, A. M. of Emanuel-College, Cambridge, chaplain to Ford, Lord Grey, publi&s;hed a &s;ermon preached before the Lord Mayor and Court of Aldermen at Bow-Church, Nov. 5, 1693, on P&s;alm lxiv. 9. dedicated to Sir William A&s;har&s;t, Knt. Lord Mayor.&mdash;He died May 12, 1724.</P>
<P>I find Thomas Knaggs, A. B. pre&s;ented to Merrington vicarage, April 6th, 1682.</P>
<P>Wood, in his Athenae Oxon. vol. ii. p. 1080, &s;ays, but certainly is mi&s;taken, that Knaggs was of Trinity-College, Oxford.</P>
<P>A &s;ermon, quarto, London, 1700, lies before me, preached at Trinity chapel, in the pari&s;h of St. Martin's in the Fields, Feb. 4, 17<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">, dedicated to Lady Sarah Brooke, "by Thomas Knaggs, A. M. and chaplain to the Right Hon<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">urable Ford, Earl of Tankerville." &mdash;The above &s;ermon, in 1693, is "by Thomas Knagg<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">, M. A. lecturer in Newca&s;tle, and chaplain to the Right Honourable Ford, Lord Grey."&mdash;"At All-Hallows," &s;ays th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> MS. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">a&s;e of Barnes, p. 52, "was Mr. Knag<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">, who, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> with Dr. Atherton, a &s;trong pa&s;&s;ive obedience man, got him&s;elf many potent on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, removed to the rectory of St. Giles', London."</P></NOTE> appointed afternoon lecturer; &s;alary 70l.</P>
<P>About April 30th, 1695, Nathanael Chilton, A. M. morning-lecturer, on the removal of N. Elli&s;on to the vicarage <NOTE N="a" PLACE="foot">He was recommended by the Bi&s;hop of Carli&s;le.</NOTE>.</P>
