<Q>"Matribus tramarinis Julius Victor votum &s;olvit libens merito."</Q>
<P>Mention occurs in Hor&s;ley's Britannia Romana of the "<HI>deae matres tramarinae</HI> or <HI>tran&s;marinae,</HI>" p. 274&mdash;the <HI>"matres dome&s;ticae"</HI> occur on an altar at Scaleby-ca&s;tle. The <HI>deae matres,</HI> as Dr. Gale ob&s;erves, were very much wor&s;hipped in Germany; and the&s;e <HI>matres tran&s;marinae</HI> &s;eem to be either the &s;ame with them, or the <HI>matres Gallicae</HI> mentioned by Montfaucon in an in&s;cription found in Spain. They are &s;uppo&s;ed to have been local godde&s;&s;es. Spon's account of them is, that they were deified women, who while living were thought to have the gift of prophecy, and after their death &s;eem to have been wor|&s;hipped as a &s;ort of genii or tutelar deities of the places where they re&s;ided. The Ger|mans paid much regard to this &s;ort of women; and it &s;eems plain from a pa&s;&s;age in Ta|citus, that the Britons had al&s;o the&s;e female enthu&s;ia&s;ts.&mdash;See Hor&s;ley, ut &s;upra, p. 201.</P>
